17. duodecim...insederat‚ ‘had taken up his position on the names and ruins of twelve villas,’ i.e. those of former owners, now absorbed into his own grounds. So F. is inclined to take this difficult passage (after Botticher). R. points out that Tiberius had no taste for extravagant buildings (vi 45); and that the meaning probably is that he united in some way and adapted to his use twelve previously existing villas. One of his villas was called Villa Iouis (Suet. Tib. 65).

RF. writes:—‘ It is not very clear what case nominibus is. In ii 16 Tacitus has the accus. after the verb, soli Cherusci iuga insedere. Perhaps the accus. is understood, and nominibus and molibus are instr. abl. st—Tiberius had occupied (the whole island) with the names and vast structures of his villas. These villas, Ι suppose, from the way in which Tacitus speaks of them, had demesnes attached to them, and so entirely filled up the island. Wherever you went, you were in the grounds of some villa or other.’
